Upon closer examination of your `Put` method, it seems that you are missing a condition for dealing with placeholders. When calculating the threshold, you must take into account the size of the HashMap, the number of placeholders (empty buckets), and the number of new entries.

Your current code only checks if the size (without accounting for placeholders) is equal to or greater than the capacity multiplied by the load factor:

```csharp
if (Size() >= this.Capacity * this.LoadFactor)
{
    ReHash();
}
```

You need to include the number of placeholders when checking for the threshold. To achieve this, add a `Placeholders` property to keep track of the number of placeholders in your HashMap. Update this property while handling removals and insertions.

Next, update your Put method to include placeholders in the threshold calculation:

```csharp
if (Size() + Placeholders + 1 >= this.Capacity * this.LoadFactor)
{
    ReHash();
}
```

This should resolve the issues with the failing tests.

You can modify the existing code to handle all three arrays: `name`, `quantity`, and `expenses`. In this example, I assume that each index in the arrays correspond to the respective `name`, `quantity`, and `expenses` of an item.

```kotlin
import com.google.firebase.firestore.FirebaseFirestore

val newItemName = "CBA"
val newItemQuantity = 1
val newExpensesValue = 100
val userId = "your_user_id"

val db = FirebaseFirestore.getInstance()
val docRef = db.collection("expenses").document(userId)

docRef.get()
    .addOnSuccessListener { document ->
        if (document.exists()) {
            val names = document.get("name") as MutableList<String>
            val quantities = document.get("quantity") as MutableList<Int>
            val expenses = document.get("expenses") as MutableList<Int>

            var itemFound = false
            var itemIndex = -1
            names.forEachIndexed { index, itemName ->
                if (itemName == newItemName) {
                  itemFound = true
                  itemIndex = index
                }
            }

            if (itemFound) {
                quantities[itemIndex] += newItemQuantity
                expenses[itemIndex] += newExpensesValue
            } else {
                names.add(newItemName)
                quantities.add(newItemQuantity)
                expenses.add(newExpensesValue)
            }

            val updateData = hashMapOf(
                "name" to names,
                "quantity" to quantities,
                "expenses" to expenses
            )

            docRef.update(updateData)
                .addOnSuccessListener {
                    Log.d("TAG", "Document updated successfully")
                }
                .addOnFailureListener { exception ->
                    Log.e("TAG", "Error updating document", exception)
                }
        } else {
            Log.d("TAG", "No such document")
        }
    }
    .addOnFailureListener { exception ->
        Log.e("TAG", "Error getting the document", exception)
    }
```

Replace `your_user_id` with the actual userId, and `newItemName`, `newItemQuantity`, and `newExpensesValue` with the values you want to add or update.

Since `Observer` is an interface, you need to implement its `update()` method in your VueClient class. The `update()` method is called by the Observable object (in your case, probably an instance of `BackendContext`) whenever it changes state, and passes any relevant information as its arguments.

Here's an example of how you could implement the `update()` method in the VueClient class:

```
public class VueClient implements Observer {

    private JPanel panel;
    private BackendContext backendContext;

    public VueClient(BackendContext backendContext) {
        this.backendContext = backendContext;

        panel = new JPanel();
        panel.add(new JButton("Button"));

        // register this object as an observer of the backend context
        backendContext.addObserver(this);
    }

    public JPanel getPanel() {
        return panel;
    }

    @Override
    public void update(Observable o, Object arg) {
        // check if the observable object is the backend context
        if (o == backendContext) {
            // check the value of the argument (if any) to determine what has changed
            if (arg instanceof String) {
                String newValue = (String) arg;
                // do something with the new value
            }
            // add more conditions for other types of arguments, as needed
        }
    }

}
```

In this example, the VueClient constructor registers the object as an observer of the backend context using the `addObserver()` method.

The `update()` method checks if the `Observable` object is the backend context and then checks the value of the `Object` argument to determine what has changed. It could be a `String`, an `Integer`, or any other object depending on how you've implemented the `BackendContext` object.

You can add your own logic within the `update()` method to handle the specific changes that have occurred and update the UI accordingly. This logic will depend on the requirements of your application.

