You can use the built-in `toLocaleDateString()` method of the `Date` object to format a date object in the desired format. Here's an example code that shows how to format a date object as "3 Mar 2023":

```
const dateObj = new Date("2023-03-03");

const options = {
  day: "numeric",
  month: "short",
  year: "numeric"
};

const formattedDate = dateObj.toLocaleDateString("en-US", options);

console.log(formattedDate); // Output: "3 Mar 2023"
```

The `toLocaleDateString()` method takes two parameters - the first parameter specifies the locale to use (in this example, "en-US"), and the second parameter is an options object that specifies the date formatting options to use. 

In the options object, you can specify which parts of the date to include in the formatted string (day, month, year), and how to display them (short, long, numeric, etc). In this example, day is displayed as numeric, month as short, and year as numeric, resulting in the desired format of "3 Mar 2023".

